text.tspan: Version 1.0 of Travis Perkins' git cheat sheet, by Nik Silver
Based on work by Jan Krüger: <jk@jk.gs>
Which is in turn based on work by Zack Rusin, http://zrusin.blogspot.com/
foo..bar from ref foo to ref bar
Diff working directory against specific commit
Remove file from working area and staging
Rename ("move") file in working area and staging
View commit history, most recent at top.
<Space> = next page, b = back, q = quit
View commit history, with ASCII graphics
Stage all changes (in tracked files) and commit
Change options using git config [--global] varname value. The following variable names are useful:
True for repositories without a working tree (usually public repositories).
Set to group or all to make the repository contents writeable for the file group or everybody.
A zlib compression level for objects (0-9, 9 = best compression) or -1 to use zlib's default.
Color-code list of branches (true = always, auto = only when outputting to a terminal)
Color-code output of git status (true, auto).
There's a little bit of room for your own notes here. This is your chance to customize this cheat sheet!
These commands will all stage the file, too
Recover file from last commit on this branch
Create new branch and switch to it
Merge from other branch, and commit with message
Create new branch and switch to it
Edit each conflicted file to resolve the conflict
Signal your resolution by staging the file
Abort problem merge and return to pre-merge state
